      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-2">Nautical Miles Explained: Why Ships Use Different Units</h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">June 14, 2025 • 4 min read</p>

      <p>If you have ever looked at a marine chart or listened to an aviation broadcast, you have encountered the nautical mile. It is not simply an old-fashioned unit — there is a very practical reason why sailors and pilots still use it today.</p>

      <h2>What is a Nautical Mile?</h2>
      <div class="bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl p-5 my-6 not-prose">
        <p class="text-center text-lg font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400">1 nautical mile = 1.852 km = 1.15078 statute miles</p>
        <p class="text-center text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-2">1 nautical mile = 1 minute of latitude</p>
      </div>
      <p>A nautical mile is defined as exactly 1,852 metres. But the reason it exists is far more elegant: it equals one minute of arc of latitude on the Earth's surface. This makes it incredibly useful for navigation on a sphere.</p>

      <h2>Why Not Just Use Regular Miles or Kilometres?</h2>
      <p>Navigation at sea and in the air involves working with latitude and longitude — angular measurements on a sphere. Because one nautical mile equals one minute of latitude:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>You can read distances directly from a chart's latitude scale</li>
        <li>One degree of latitude always equals 60 nautical miles</li>
        <li>Plotting a course becomes simple arithmetic rather than complex conversion</li>
        <li>Speed in knots (nautical miles per hour) integrates naturally with chart distances</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Nautical Miles vs Statute Miles vs Kilometres</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>1 nautical mile = 1.852 km</li>
        <li>1 nautical mile = 1.151 statute miles</li>
        <li>1 statute mile = 0.869 nautical miles</li>
        <li>1 kilometre = 0.54 nautical miles</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>What About Knots?</h2>
      <p>A knot is simply one nautical mile per hour. The name comes from the old practice of measuring ship speed by throwing a knotted rope overboard and counting how many knots passed through a sailor's hands in a set time.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>1 knot = 1 nautical mile/hour = 1.852 km/h = 1.151 mph</li>
        <li>Cruise ship: 20-24 knots (37-44 km/h)</li>
        <li>Cargo ship: 12-16 knots (22-30 km/h)</li>
        <li>Commercial aircraft: 450-550 knots (830-1,020 km/h)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Who Uses Nautical Miles?</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Maritime navigation</strong> — all shipping worldwide</li>
        <li><strong>Aviation</strong> — all air traffic control and flight planning</li>
        <li><strong>Weather services</strong> — for reporting visibility and wind at sea</li>
        <li><strong>International law</strong> — territorial waters are defined in nautical miles (12 NM from shore)</li>
      </ul>

      <p>The nautical mile is one of those rare units where the definition is not arbitrary — it is baked into the geometry of our planet. That is why, even in an age of GPS, it remains the standard for anyone navigating Earth's surface over long distances.</p>

